<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="536" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,404,429]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[330,433,404,428]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[330,433,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Plakortis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
thinly encrusting, gray in color, cartilaginous in consistency, with a vaguely reticulated tangential ectosomal skeleton and a disorganized choanosomal skeleton with fiber-like structures; spicules are diods and triods, some of which spined, and tuberculate microrhabds; smooth siliceous spheres are also present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="536" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,511,536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Description.</emphasis>
Shape thinly encrusting (
<figureCitation box="[643,711,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[698,711,512,536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A), 4.0 by 
<quantity box="[842,920,511,536]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
wide by 
<quantity box="[1033,1112,511,536]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" unit="cm" value="0.5">0.5 cm</quantity>
thick. External and internal color gray 
<emphasis box="[275,352,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">in vivo</emphasis>
, becoming light brown to cream after fixation in ethanol. Surface irregular, rugose, coriaceous. Oscules contracted, not visible in the preserved specimen. Consistency cartilaginous, slightly compressible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,620,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Skeleton.</emphasis>
Tangential ectosomal skeleton reticulate, with ill-defined multispicular spicule tracts forming circular meshes, 
<number box="[358,423,656,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="34.5" valueMax="39.0" valueMin="30.0">30-39</number>
- 
<number box="[431,461,656,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="70.0">70</number>
µm in diameter (n= 
<number box="[722,753,656,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="20.0">20</number>
; 
<figureCitation box="[773,848,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[834,848,656,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B). In transverse sections, the ectosome is well differentiated and shows ascending spicule columns separated by ectosomal lacunae, 
<date box="[1115,1222,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="1939-12-22">
<number box="[1115,1185,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="17.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="12.0">12–22</number>
- 
<number box="[1192,1222,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="39.0">39</number>
</date>
µm (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1350,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[1336,1350,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, top). Subectosomal lacunae are absent. Choanosomal skeleton dense, disorganized, with a few denser, sinuous tracts parallel to the surface (
<figureCitation box="[415,483,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[469,483,764,788]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, bottom). Some parts of the mesohyl show a golden color and look similar to illdefined spongin fibres (
<figureCitation box="[423,491,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[478,491,800,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
D), but could not be easily separated form the mesohyl like common demosponge spongin fibers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,871,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Spicules.</emphasis>
Diods thin, slightly sinuous, with sharp endings and protuberant central torsion. Some diods have small spines along the actines or near the center (
<figureCitation box="[701,767,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[753,767,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
E): 
<number box="[809,895,908,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="35.8" valueMax="42.6" valueMin="29.0">29-42.6</number>
- 
<number box="[903,946,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="103.0">103</number>
/ 
<number box="[964,998,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1-2</number>
- 
<number box="[1007,1022,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="4.0">4</number>
µm (n = 
<number box="[1127,1159,908,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="20.0">20</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Triods smooth, Y-shaped, with sharp endings and center deformed like that of diods. Some triods also have small spines along the actines or near their intersection (
<figureCitation box="[713,779,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[765,779,980,1004]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
F): actines 
<number box="[903,1011,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="31.1" valueMax="37.5" valueMin="24.7">24.7-37.5</number>
- 
<number box="[1018,1069,980,1004]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="49.4">49.4</number>
/ 
<number box="[1091,1128,980,1004]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1-3</number>
- 
<number box="[1137,1151,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="5.0">5</number>
µm (n= 
<number box="[1244,1275,980,1004]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="20.0">20</number>
). Microrhabds irregular, straight or curved, highly tuberculate (
<figureCitation box="[840,906,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[892,906,1016,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
G): 
<number box="[950,1008,1015,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="5.85" valueMax="6.7" valueMin="5.0">5-6.7</number>
- 
<number box="[1017,1046,1016,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="14.0">14</number>
/ 
<number box="[1068,1106,1016,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2-3</number>
- 
<number box="[1114,1129,1015,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="6.0">6</number>
µm (n= 
<number box="[1221,1252,1016,1040]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="20.0">20</number>
). Smooth siliceous spheres are common (
<figureCitation box="[595,662,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[648,662,1052,1076]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
H): 
<number box="[706,762,1052,1076]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="10.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="1.0">1–20</number>
µm (n= 
<number box="[854,885,1052,1076]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="20.0">20</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,448,1087,1112]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Habitat and ecology.</emphasis>
The only specimen was collected on a vertical wall inside a semi-obscure cave, 
<quantity box="[1377,1436,1087,1112]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
depth. The sponge had no associated macrofauna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="536" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" box="[199,1141,1159,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1159,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic from Fernando de Noronha Archipelago, NE 
<collectingCountry box="[975,1043,1159,1184]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1058,1124,1159,1184]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,185,1333]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[154,1439,185,1334]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Collection sites of the four new species of Plakortis. Orange, Plakortis petrupaulensis sp. nov. (São Pedro e São Paulo Archipelago); blue, Plakortis spinalis sp. nov. (Fernando de Noronha Archipelago); yellow, Plakortis potiguarensis sp. nov. (Potiguar Basin, Rio Grande do Norte State); green, Plakinastrella globularis sp. nov. (off Salvador, Bahia State and Almirante Saldanha Seamount, Rio de Janeiro State). The states where the new species occur are labeled: RN, Rio Grande do Norte; BA, Bahia; RJ, Rio de Janeiro." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218897/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[1111,1124,1160,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,1196,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[456,654,1196,1220]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="spinalis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[456,654,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Plakortis spinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[663,755,1196,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[663,755,1196,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
belongs to the group of 
<taxonomicName box="[1041,1144,1196,1220]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1041,1144,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Plakortis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with microrhabds, which now also includes 
<taxonomicName box="[364,559,1232,1256]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="petrupaulensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[364,559,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. petrupaulensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[568,659,1231,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[568,659,1231,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
as well as 
<taxonomicName box="[790,857,1232,1256]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lita">
<emphasis box="[790,857,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. lita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[873,1085,1232,1256]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="microrhabdifera">
<emphasis box="[873,1085,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. microrhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1219,1232,1256]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="hooperi">
<emphasis box="[1102,1219,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. hooperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1277,1373,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. m y r a e</emphasis>
. The new species is mostly similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[571,773,1268,1292]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="petrupaulensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[571,773,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. petrupaulensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[789,888,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[789,888,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by its thinly encrusting shape, disorganized choanosomal skeleton, and especially the tuberculate microrhabds; 
<taxonomicName box="[902,1093,1304,1328]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="petrupaulensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[902,1093,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. petrupaulensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1100,1189,1303,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1100,1189,1303,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, however, differs by a smooth surface, light brown color, absence of triods, and absence of spined spicules. 
<taxonomicName box="[1135,1334,1340,1364]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="spinalis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1135,1334,1340,1364]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Plakortis spinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1344,1436,1340,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1344,1436,1340,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[303,373,1376,1400]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lita">
<emphasis box="[303,373,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. lita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[393,610,1376,1400]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="microrhabdifera">
<emphasis box="[393,610,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. microrhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[629,732,1377,1400]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="myrae">
<emphasis box="[629,732,1377,1400]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. myrae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[797,917,1376,1400]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="hooperi">
<emphasis box="[797,917,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">P. hooperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its gray color, presence of tubercles on microrhabds and presence of spines on diods and triods. It differs from all other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1175,1278,1412,1436]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1175,1278,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Plakortis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the spined diods and triods, tuberculate microrhabds, and by the fiber-like structures in the choanosome (
<figureCitation box="[1204,1271,1447,1472]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plakortis spinalis sp. nov.: A, preserved holotype (MNRJ 8597); B, tangential section of the ectosome; C, transverse section of ectosome and choanosome; D, fiber-like structure in the choanosome; E, diods; F, triods; G, tuberculate microrhabds; H, sphere (E – H, SEM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
Fig. 
<number box="[1257,1271,1448,1472]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1261,1484,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1509]" box="[199,1261,1484,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1484,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName box="[459,546,1484,1508]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="6" pageNumber="536" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="spinalis">
<emphasis box="[459,546,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="536">spinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the presence of small spines on some diods and triods.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
